  "summary": "Hercule Poirot meets with Jeremy Claude to discuss the possibility of a lost will belonging to Gordon Claude. Poirot suggests that documents believed to be destroyed might be recoverable through new methods, specifically mentioning a file in a safe. Jeremy disputes this, asserting that there was no safe at the Sheffield Terrace house and that Gordon kept his important documents in his office. Despite Jeremy's skepticism, Poirot obtains permission to investigate the records of the Air Raid Prevention Bureau.\n\nDuring the meeting, Jeremy’s wife, Francis Claude, joins them. Appearing ill, she expresses concern for Rosalind, who is alone at Frognack following David Hunter’s arrest. Francis reacts with curiosity and suspicion when Poirot mentions Colonel Porter. After Poirot departs, Francis and Jeremy privately admit that they do not believe Poirot’s stated reasons for returning to London or his theories regarding a new will.\n\nPoirot travels to London to investigate the incident at Sheffield Terrace. He confirms the house was destroyed in an air raid, which killed three servants: Frederick Gems, Elizabeth Gems, and Eileen Corrigan. Poirot intends to contact the servants' relatives and seeks to interview Colonel Porter regarding his observations during the raid. However, upon arriving at Porter's residence, Poirot finds a police presence. He learns from a local inspector and Chief Constable Greville that Colonel Porter has committed suicide by shooting himself with his own revolver, allegedly due to depression and the pressure of testifying in the investigation.",
